25|$|Without overstating it (and without fully {{defending}} it) {{not only}} is there a consensus about the need for a conception of the good, there may even be a consensus about the particular conception of the good that should inform policies on these nonconstitutional political issues. Communitarians endorse civic republicanism {{and a growing number of}} liberals endorse some version of deliberative democracy. Both envision a need for citizens who are independent and responsible and for public forums that present citizens with opportunities to enter into <b>public</b> <b>deliberations</b> on social policies.|$|R
50|$|AmericaSpeaks {{partnered with}} the Fund for Our Economic Future to {{organize}} a series of town meetings and public forums across northeast Ohio to enable thousands of people to come {{together to create a}} strategic plan for revitalizing the region's economy. One of the largest <b>public</b> <b>deliberations</b> convened, Voices & Choices combined a variety of approaches for mobilizing the region’s citizenry, including one-on-one interviews, online forums and two large-scale 21st Century Town Meetings. Over 20,000 participants identified the region’s strengths, identified and prioritized its most important challenges and brainstormed solutions.|$|R
